  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- First legal framework addressing financial reporting requirements\n- Focused on detecting and preventing criminal financial activities\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created comprehensive international standards\n- Developed recommendations for combating money laundering\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- 1990s: Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations introduced\n\n4. Post-9/11 Changes\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded AML regulations\n- Increased financial institution oversight\n- Strengthened terrorist financing prevention\n\n5. Recent Developments\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- More stringent international cooperation\n- Advanced technological screening mechanisms\n\n6. Global Compliance Trends\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Broader definition of financial crimes\n- Greater emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n\nThese legislative developments represent a continuous adaptation to emerging financial crime techniques.",
